output.crosstab_text:
For Level 8 graduates of Allied health, 5 years after graduation, the industry with the highest proportion of female graduates is Public administration and defence - compulsory social security, and the median earnings of females in this industry were £25,500. The industry with the highest proportion of male graduates was Human health and social work activities and the median earnings of males in this industry were £24,900.

The biggest difference in proportions is seen in Public administration and defence - compulsory social security where the proportion of female graduates is 18.6 percentage points higher than the proportion of male graduates.

The biggest difference in median earnings is seen in Wholesale and retail trade - repair of motor vehicles and motorcycles where the median earnings of male graduates were £2,100 higher than the medain earnings of female graduates.

The group with the highest earnings was male graduates in the Manufacturing industry (median earnings of £26,400).

5.9% of female graduates are concentrated in the top 2 industries (either Education or Manufacturing), whereas for male graduates this is 30.8%.
output.crosstab_title: Industry of graduate employment for graduates of Allied health by sex , 5 years after graduation, male and female Level 8 graduates from English HEIs, APs and FECs, 2018/19 tax year.
